.IX Title "Tie::Collection 3"
.TH Tie::Collection 3 "perl v5.5.30" "2000-07-09" "User Contributed Perl Documentation"
.UC
.SH "NAME"
Tie::Collection \- A trivial implementaion of Tie::Cache by using a tied
handle of a hash for storage.
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
use Tie::Collection;
use DB_File;
use Fcntl;
.PP
$dbm = tie \f(CW%hash2\fR, DB_File, 'file.db', O_RDWR | O_CREAT, 0644;
tie \f(CW%hash\fR, Tie::Collection, \f(CW$dbm\fR, {MaxBytes => \f(CW$cache_size\fR};
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
Tie::Collection implements a trivial implementation of \fBTie::Cache\fR by 
Joshua Chamas, that gets a tied hash handle to store the data. Assumption
was that most common use will be disk storage, therfore the storage hash
will probably be tied.
.PP
Tie::Collection is useful with \fBDB_File\fR or \fB\s-1MLDBM\s0\fR, as will as with
\&\fBTie::DBI\fR. It was designed to be used with \fB\s-1HTML::HTPL\s0\fR in order to
cache objects accesses via a key, so they don't have to be read from disk
again and again.
.PP
Tie::Collection needs two parameters: The handled of the tied hash, and a
hashref with parameters to pass to \fBTie::Cache\fR. (See manpage).
